  {
    q: "How do you diagnose LA gas line pressure issues?",
    a: "We test gas pressure at the supply with a manometer on every gas-stove diagnostic call. LA neighborhood gas pressure varies meaningfully: older Beverly Hills installations, newer Long Beach commercial buildouts, Pasadena historic restaurant blocks all have different baseline pressures. Low supply pressure causes igniter and thermocouple failures that look like part failures. Replacing the igniter without addressing the pressure issue guarantees the new igniter fails the same way. We address root cause. New gas line installation or upsizing is a different trade (plumbing contractor with gas certification), but we diagnose the issue and provide written documentation for your plumber."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the typical service life of a commercial gas stove?",
    a: "Vulcan, Garland, Wolf Commercial premium tier: 15 to 18 years on average with regular service. Imperial and American Range mid-tier: 12 to 15 years. The frame and burner head construction outlast components by years on the premium brands. Igniters and thermocouples are year 4 to 8 wear items but those are routine replacements that don't end the stove's life. The constraint at year 15+ is usually gas valve assembly degradation across multiple burners."
  },
  {
    q: "My countertop hot plate is sluggish to heat up. Is it failing?",
    a: "Probably not. Sluggish heat-up on a Vulcan VHP or Garland MCO countertop hot plate is most often the burner head clogged with grease and carbon buildup (year 1 to 3 if not cleaned regularly), or low gas pressure at the supply, or a weakening thermocouple causing the gas valve to throttle prematurely. We diagnose all three on the visit. Cleaning resolves about 30% of sluggish-heat calls at no parts cost."
