<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Commercial gas stove service</p>
    <h2>The most common commercial cooktop type in LA kitchens.</h2>

    <p>Gas commercial stoves dominate LA professional kitchens. Standalone countertop hot plates (2 to 4 burners), modular cooking suite sections (6 to 12 burners), drop-in cooktop sections integrated into custom kitchens. Operating profile is typically 12 to 16 hour service days at peak burner output, which means igniters and thermocouples are wear items on a predictable timeline regardless of brand.</p>

    <p>We service commercial gas stoves across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside. Top brands: <strong>Vulcan</strong> (VHP series countertop hot plates, VTC modular cooktops). <strong>Garland</strong> (Master Series MCO countertop). <strong>Wolf Commercial</strong> (6-burner modular sections). <strong>Imperial</strong> (standalone gas cooktops). <strong>American Range</strong> (full lineup). Plus Anets, MagiKitch'n, Star, and other secondary brands as standard coverage.</p>

    <p>Note on terminology: "stove" and "range" are often used interchangeably in commercial contexts. Strictly, a stove is the cooktop only and a range is the cooktop plus oven beneath. The burner-side service tree is largely the same across both. For range service (with oven), see our <a href="/commercial/range-repair/">commercial range repair</a> page. This page covers stovetop-only equipment: countertop hot plates that sit on a counter or shelf, modular cooktop sections that integrate into a custom hot-line cooking suite, and drop-in cooktop sections that are flush-mounted into an island or counter.</p>

    <p>Configuration matters for service planning. A 2-burner countertop hot plate has different access geometry than a 12-burner hot-line modular section integrated into a custom cooking suite. Modular sections in custom suites sometimes require partial disassembly of adjacent equipment (charbroiler, griddle) to access gas connections behind the unit. We plan around this on the diagnostic visit and quote labor honestly when adjacent equipment access adds time.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. BHGS #A49573. EPA 608 Universal #1346255700410.  scope. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. Pre-open dispatch standard for restaurants opening at 11 AM with a stove that won't ignite during morning prep. We don't add an emergency surcharge for pre-open or weekend service, which puts us behind some competitors on margin but keeps the trust signal honest.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 FAILURE TREE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Failure tree</p>
    <h2>Common commercial gas stove failures.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Six failure modes cover roughly 90% of service calls. Diagnosis order matters because LA gas pressure issues mimic igniter failures and replacing the igniter without testing pressure guarantees a callback.</p>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Igniter failure (per burner, year 4 to 7).</strong> Most common single-burner symptom. Hot-surface or spark module depending on burner architecture. $200 to $360 per igniter.</li>
      <li><strong>Thermocouple wear (year 5 to 8).</strong> Thermocouple proves flame to the gas valve. When weakening, the gas valve closes prematurely. $180 to $290.</li>
      <li><strong>Pilot light extinguishing (older standing-pilot models).</strong> Some older Vulcan and Garland units still use standing pilot architecture. Pilot service or conversion to electronic ignition.</li>
      <li><strong>Burner head clog (grease and carbon, year 1 to 3 if uncleaned).</strong> Sluggish heat-up, uneven flame distribution. Cleaning resolves; about 30% of "sluggish stove" calls clear at no parts cost.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas valve degradation (year 8+).</strong> Multi-burner symptoms (multiple burners running off-spec at the same time) often trace to gas valve assembly degradation rather than per-burner part failures.</li>
      <li><strong>LA gas pressure issues (any age).</strong> Low supply pressure causes igniter and thermocouple failures across multiple burners. We test pressure on every call.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Practitioner note on multi-burner symptoms: when 3 or more burners on a 6-burner Wolf Commercial or Garland modular section misbehave at the same time, the cause is rarely "3 igniters all failed at once." It's usually a supply-side issue (gas pressure, regulator drift) or a manifold-side issue (gas valve assembly serving multiple burners). Replacing 3 igniters when the actual issue is regulator drift wastes parts cost and guarantees a callback within weeks. We diagnose to root cause before quoting parts.</p>

    <p>Carbon and grease accumulation deserves a separate mention because it's the most preventable failure mode. LA commercial kitchens running 12+ hours of daily prep at 6-burner cooktops accumulate carbon on burner heads at a rate that causes sluggish heat-up at year 1 to 3 if not cleaned regularly. Quarterly burner head cleaning (15 to 30 minutes per burner at most operations) prevents the year-3 sluggishness call entirely. We include burner head inspection on every diagnostic visit and recommend cleaning when accumulation is visible.</p>
  </div>
</section>

